# Aliro reader component options (ESP-IDF). Applies to every app that pulls the
# aliro_reader component (the standalone reader and the Matter lock).

menu "Aliro reader"

config ALIRO_LAT_TRACE
	bool "Walk-up latency trace (aliro-lat budget line)"
	default y
	help
	  One-shot timestamps at every walk-up phase boundary (BLE connect ->
	  discovery -> L2CAP -> AUTH0/EXCHANGE -> M1-M4 -> first range ->
	  threshold -> bolt), printed as a single consolidated "aliro-lat"
	  budget line after the bolt is driven. Diagnostics only: one uptime
	  read + store per boundary, nothing on the UWB re-arm hot path.
	  Disable to compile the trace out entirely.

config WOZ_ALIRO_LAB
	bool "Aliro Lab transaction trace"
	default y
	depends on ALIRO_LAT_TRACE
	help
	  Compile in the structured "[ALAB] t=<us> ev=..." trace at transaction
	  phase boundaries so tools/aliro_lab.py can turn a captured serial log
	  into a scored walk-up report (phase waterfall, approach curve, checks).
	  Like the sibling `uwbdiag` trace, it ships in every Aliro build but
	  stays OFF at boot — the `lab on`/`lab off` console command toggles it
	  at runtime, off the UWB hot path. Its per-phase lines come from the
	  aliro-lat stamps, hence the ALIRO_LAT_TRACE dependency. Set n to strip
	  it entirely from a hardened production image.

config WOZ_ALIRO_STEPUP
	bool "Enable the Aliro step-up (Access Document) phase"
	default n
	help
	  Reference-completeness build of the Aliro v1.0 §8.4 step-up phase: after
	  the standard EXCHANGE, the reader can request an ISO 18013-5 (mdoc) Access
	  Document from the User Device (ENVELOPE / GET RESPONSE APDUs carrying a
	  session-encrypted DeviceRequest/DeviceResponse), then parse and verify it
	  per §7.4 on a background worker.

	  This is OFF by default and, when on, is armed one-shot from the console
	  (`aliro-stepup arm`); it never runs per-unlock. The verification verdict is
	  logged and stored only -- it NEVER gates the unlock, which the provisioned
	  trust store alone decides. With this option unset the reader is byte-for-byte
	  identical to today and the fast-path auth segment is untouched.

endmenu
